    <h1>Zero Trust Networking-Security</h1>
    <div class=3D"Section1">
        <div class=3D"panel" style=3D"border-color: #086A87;border-style: s=
olid;border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"panelHeader" style=3D"border-bottom-width: 1px;border-bottom-=
style: solid;border-bottom-color: #086A87;background-color: #086A87;color: =
white;">
<b>WHAT IS ZERO TRUST NETWORKING?</b>
</div>
<div class=3D"panelContent">=20
<p>Zero trust (ZT) networking means removing trusted network zones and trea=
ting every host as potentially compromised. &nbsp;the underlying philosophy=
 of ZT is that everything is a potential risk. <span style=3D"color: rgb(10=
2,102,102);">Any system or user that interacts with your data must be consi=
dered possibly malicious.&nbsp; The local corporate network is now consider=
ed as dangerous as the internet, and sensitive data is always at risk.</spa=
n></p>
<p>ZT networking takes the security controls typically found at the Interne=
t edge or between zones and makes them available at each host. &nbsp;Instea=
d of one enforcement point at the perimeter of networks, three complimentar=
y enforcement points are used: at the perimeter, in the hypervisor, and on =
the host.</p>=20
</div>
</div>
<div class=3D"panel" style=3D"border-color: #086A87;border-style: solid;bor=
der-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"panelHeader" style=3D"border-bottom-width: 1px;border-bottom-=
style: solid;border-bottom-color: #086A87;background-color: #086A87;color: =
white;">
<b>HOW IS THE ZERO TRUST NETWORK DESIGNED?</b>
</div>
<div class=3D"panelContent">=20
<p class=3D"auto-cursor-target"><span><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);"><s=
pan class=3D"confluence-embedded-file-wrapper confluence-embedded-manual-si=
ze"><img class=3D"confluence-embedded-image confluence-external-resource" a=
lt=3D"Products.png" height=3D"485" width=3D"624" src=3D"https://lh3.googleu=
sercontent.com/6DmaLFWRmmPzuYW-Sv0vYZoV4i01DigF3n85Ba8tKpBGd5lhOFX8B0SnLEsh=
shyqYwS3qDUxxWqjPhYKb3EZaRD5svTR4z-jxU08I9XANot-z3NU_gFtwW8YHaGuZDePcd5hKCN=
Z" data-image-src=3D"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/6DmaLFWRmmPzuYW-Sv0v=
YZoV4i01DigF3n85Ba8tKpBGd5lhOFX8B0SnLEshshyqYwS3qDUxxWqjPhYKb3EZaRD5svTR4z-=
jxU08I9XANot-z3NU_gFtwW8YHaGuZDePcd5hKCNZ"></span></span></span></p>
<div class=3D"panel" style=3D"border-color: #086A87;border-style: solid;bor=
der-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"panelHeader" style=3D"border-bottom-width: 1px;border-bottom-=
style: solid;border-bottom-color: #086A87;background-color: #086A87;color: =
white;">
<b>PRINCIPLES &amp; GOALS</b>
</div>
<div class=3D"panelContent">=20
<p><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);">The principles and goals of a Zero Tr=
ust Networking strategy are as follows.</span></p>
<ol>
<li style=3D"list-style-type: decimal;"><p>DO NOT trust anything. Implicitl=
y or explicitly trust no user, device, IP address, system, location, or oth=
er entity completely. There is NO security perimeter (trusted zone).&nbsp;<=
/p></li>
<li style=3D"list-style-type: decimal;"><p>A role-based, least privilege, a=
pproach to security is best practice.</p></li>
<li>Document communications requirements of the application, users, monitor=
ing systems, or other entities within the system.</li>
<li style=3D"list-style-type: decimal;"><p>Automated configuration and cent=
ralized management of security settings ensures consistency and compliance =
to standards.</p></li>
<li style=3D"list-style-type: decimal;"><p>Multiple layers of enforcement p=
rotects against compromise of any single, and potentially multiple, securit=
y features.</p></li>
<li style=3D"list-style-type: decimal;"><p>Security based on roles and resp=
onsibilities, rather than static IP addresses, provides a more dynamic and =
flexible architecture.</p></li>
</ol>=20
</div>
</div>
<h1 class=3D"auto-cursor-target" id=3D"ZeroTrustNetworking-Security-Complim=
entaryEnforcementPoints">Complimentary Enforcement Points</h1>
<h2 id=3D"ZeroTrustNetworking-Security-InternetEdgeEnforcement"><strong>Int=
ernet Edge Enforcement</strong></h2>
<p><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);">The Internet edge is upgraded from a =
legacy firewall to a next-gen firewall (NGFW). &nbsp;A NGFW combines tradit=
ional firewall functionality with capabilities previously provided by separ=
ate systems. &nbsp;Some of these capabilities are:</span></p>
<ul>
<li style=3D"list-style-type: disc;"><p><span>Layer 3/4 stateful firewall</=
span></p></li>
<li style=3D"list-style-type: disc;"><p><span>Intrusion Detection and Preve=
ntion Systems (IDPS)</span></p></li>
<li style=3D"list-style-type: disc;"><p><span>Anti-malware</span></p></li>
<li style=3D"list-style-type: disc;"><p><span>Data Loss Prevention (DLP)</s=
pan></p></li>
<li style=3D"list-style-type: disc;"><p><span>Web content filtering</span><=
/p></li>
<li style=3D"list-style-type: disc;"><p><span>Zero-day protection</span></p=
></li>
</ul>
<p><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);">A NGFW also has these new abilities t=
hat are neither available on legacy firewalls nor provided by other systems=
:</span></p>
<ul>
<li style=3D"list-style-type: disc;"><p><span>Ability to look inside commun=
ications and identify applications by the content of the data, rather than =
just by port number.</span></p></li>
<li style=3D"list-style-type: disc;"><p><span>Ability to identify traffic b=
ased on the user to IP address mapping, and enforce policies based on speci=
fic user or group membership.</span></p></li>
<li style=3D"list-style-type: disc;"><p><span>Integrated Application Progra=
mming Interface (API) that allows dynamic identification of systems based o=
n the application and role of the system within that application.</span></p=
></li>
</ul>
<p><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);">In addition to the NGFW, a Web Applic=
ation Firewall (WAF) will be added that will protect web servers from commo=
n vulnerabilities. &nbsp;The Internet edge also consists of our remote acce=
ss systems, which consists of XenApp and XenDesktop and utilize RSA Tokens =
or OneClick certificates for NAC.</span></p>
<p><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);">JM Family selected Palo Alto Networks=
 for our NGFW after a comprehensive process in which we considered all of t=
he major vendors. &nbsp;We are still investigating WAF solutions, and will =
likely start testing later this year.</span></p>
<h2 id=3D"ZeroTrustNetworking-Security-HypervisionEnforcement"><strong><spa=
n style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);">Hypervision Enforcement</span></strong></h2>
<p><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);">The hypervisor enforcement is somethi=
ng new that we have not done before at JM Family. &nbsp;Using technology su=
ch as VMware NSX in our new Mesa data center, we can provide the same capab=
ilities of a legacy firewall down to individual hosts. &nbsp;This is effect=
ively micro-segmentation, and is a key component of a zero trust network. &=
nbsp;In public clouds, the same capability is present, and called Security =
Groups in AWS and Network Access Lists (ACLs) in Microsoft Azure.</span></p=
>
<p><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);">We are researching additional capabil=
ities that will provide NGFW functionality at each host. &nbsp;Palo Alto Ne=
tworks, as well as most of the major NGFW vendors, have hypervisor modules =
that plug into the VMware NSX system to provide these capabilities. &nbsp;A=
fter we fully test the interoperability we will be implementing a solution =
in our new data centers. &nbsp;This type of technology is not currently ava=
ilable in public cloud environments. &nbsp;However, we will be examining an=
y new features available in the future, and supplementing the capabilities =
on the hosts in all environments as detailed below.</span></p>
<h2 id=3D"ZeroTrustNetworking-Security-HostEnforcement"><strong><span style=
=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);">Host Enforcement</span></strong></h2>
<p><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);">On the host, we will be supplementing=
 the protection we currently deploy with new and upgraded capabilities. &nb=
sp;In a zero trust network the host has the following components:</span></p=
>
<ul>
<li style=3D"list-style-type: disc;"><p><span>Layer 3/4 firewall</span></p>=
</li>
<li style=3D"list-style-type: disc;"><p><span>DLP agent</span></p></li>
<li style=3D"list-style-type: disc;"><p><span>Anti-malware agent</span></p>=
</li>
<li style=3D"list-style-type: disc;"><p><span>IDPS agent</span></p></li>
</ul>
<p><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);">You will notice that these are some o=
f the same capabilities available in the NGFW at the perimeter and at the h=
ypervisor are present on the host. &nbsp;This is a multi-layered approach t=
hat helps ensure that a failure in one system does not open systems to comp=
romise. &nbsp;This has a potential drawback in increasing the complexity of=
 a system. &nbsp;However, with automation and configuration management tool=
s we avoid the management issue of configuring the same rules at multiple l=
ayers.</span></p>
<h2 id=3D"ZeroTrustNetworking-Security-Cloud/SaaSSystems"><strong><span sty=
le=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);">Cloud/SaaS Systems</span></strong></h2>
<p><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);">Outside of our systems, whether in th=
e public cloud Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS) environments like AWS and=
 Azure, or the internal private clouds we are building, there are other sys=
tems. &nbsp;These fall in the category of Software as a Service (SaaS) and =
sometimes just referred to as =E2=80=9CCloud Services.=E2=80=9D &nbsp;&nbsp=
;Examples of these systems are ServiceNow, <a href=3D"http://Salesforce.com=
" class=3D"external-link" rel=3D"nofollow">Salesforce.com</a>, and similar =
services in which we do not host, manage, or maintain the systems.</span></=
p>
<p><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);">We are currently investigating soluti=
ons to monitor these services, and particularly the content stored in the s=
ystems, so that no confidential information that we do not want stored in t=
he systems are in fact contained within the systems. &nbsp;This is importan=
t for information such as social security numbers, credit card numbers, etc=
.</span></p>=20
</div>
</div>
<div class=3D"panel" style=3D"border-color: #086A87;border-style: solid;bor=
der-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"panelHeader" style=3D"border-bottom-width: 1px;border-bottom-=
style: solid;border-bottom-color: #086A87;background-color: #086A87;color: =
white;">
<b>ARE THERE ADDITIONAL SECURITY MANAGEMENT CONSIDERATIONS? </b>
</div>
<div class=3D"panelContent">=20
<p><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);">Outside of enforcement points, we als=
o have existing and planned security management solutions. &nbsp;These incl=
ude categories such as:</span></p>
<ul>
<li style=3D"list-style-type: disc;"><p><span>Security Information and Even=
t Management (SIEM) that collects security related events and performs corr=
elation to detect possible intrusions or abnormal behavior.</span></p></li>
<li style=3D"list-style-type: disc;"><p><span>Static Code Analysis that sca=
ns code or configurations for best practices and adherence to standards.</s=
pan></p></li>
<li style=3D"list-style-type: disc;"><p><span>Dynamic penetration testing t=
o find systems or services that are vulnerable to exploitation and compromi=
se.</span></p></li>
<li style=3D"list-style-type: disc;"><p><span>Configuration compliance test=
ing to ensure systems are configured and adhere to common standards.</span>=
</p></li>
</ul>=20
</div>
</div>
<p><br></p>
